Note: ============================================================================
Note: R SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for R statistical computing language
Note: Handles R-specific features:
Note: - Data frames and vectors
Note: - Statistical functions and packages
Note: - Environments and scoping
Note: - S3/S4 object systems
Note: - Dynamic typing with type inference
Note: - Package imports (library/require)
Note: - Formula syntax (y ~ x)

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HirNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_builder.runa" as HirBuilder

@Reasoning:
Top-level state passed to every analyze_* routine. Holds the active environment chain, accumulated diagnostics, a type-inference memo cache, and registries for R's two object systems (S3 dispatch and S4 formal classes). Parent_context enables nested-context analysis when entering a function body without losing outer state.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Aggregate of environment chain (REnvironment linked list), parent_context for nested analysis, package list, current function name for diagnostics, separate error and warning lists, plus three dictionaries for type cache and S3/S4 class registries.
@End Implementation

Type called "RSemanticContext":
    current_environment as REnvironment
    parent_context as RSemanticContext
    global_packages as List[String]
    current_function as String
    error_list as List[String]
    warning_list as List[String]
    type_cache as Dictionary[String, RType]
    s3_classes as Dictionary[String, RS3ClassInfo]
    s4_classes as Dictionary[String, RS4ClassInfo]
End Type

@Reasoning:
R's "environment" is a first-class scope object with both variable and function bindings. Environments form a parent chain that lookup_r_variable / lookup_r_function walk to model R's lexical scoping. The is_global flag short-circuits the global environment's distinct semantics for assign(), <<-, etc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two dictionaries (one for vars, one for funs) keyed by name. Parent_env is the enclosing scope (NULL at global). Name is a debug label.
@End Implementation

Type called "REnvironment":
    variables as Dictionary[String, RVariable]
    functions as Dictionary[String, RFunction]
    parent_env as REnvironment
    name as String
    is_global as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
Symbol-table entry for a single binding. Tracks not just the inferred type but also lifetime markers (first_assignment_line/last_access_line) used by validate_variable_usage to flag write-only or unused bindings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six fields: name, inferred RType, is_constant flag (set for variables assigned with R's `<-` only once), scope tag (for diagnostics), and two source-line markers maintained by analyze_r_variable_declaration and analyze_r_assignment.
@End Implementation

Type called "RVariable":
    name as String
    type as RType
    is_constant as Boolean
    scope as String
    first_assignment_line as Integer
    last_access_line as Integer
End Type

Note: Local R AST schema. The semantic analyzer expects an enriched node
Note: type carrying language-specific fields; until v0.0.9.x rewires it to
Note: the generic HIRNode + children traversal, this local type satisfies
Note: the analyzer's field accesses.
@Reasoning:
Local AST schema specific to the R semantic analyzer. The leading prose Note already documents this exists because the v0.0.9.x rewire to the generic HIRNode + children traversal has not landed yet - this struct captures every field the analyzer accesses by name (function_name, package_name, predictors, response, etc.) so each analyze_* routine can extract its operands directly without children-array indexing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Twenty-two pointer/integer fields covering every R-specific construct: statements/body/arguments/parameters (function and block), target/operator (assignment), accessor/access_type/dataframe (df$col, df[i, j]), package_name/is_require (library calls), interactions/predictors/response (formulas), and literal_type (numeric/string/logical).
@End Implementation

Type called "RASTNode":
    node_type as String
    name as Integer
    value as Integer
    line as Integer
    type as Integer
    statements as Integer
    body as Integer
    arguments as Integer
    parameters as Integer
    function_name as Integer
    initializer as Integer
    operator as Integer
    target as Integer
    accessor as Integer
    access_type as Integer
    dataframe as Integer
    package_name as Integer
    is_require as Integer
    interactions as Integer
    predictors as Integer
    response as Integer
    literal_type as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Function-symbol table entry. Captures the parameter list (for arity and default detection) and the inferred return type. The two boolean method flags distinguish R's three function flavours: plain function, S3 generic dispatch target, S4 formal method.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Seven fields: name, parameter list, return RType, is_generic (S3 dispatch via UseMethod), is_s3_method (e.g. print.data.frame), is_s4_method (e.g. setMethod), and originating package.
@End Implementation

Type called "RFunction":
    name as String
    parameters as List[RParameter]
    return_type as RType
    is_generic as Boolean
    is_s3_method as Boolean
    is_s4_method as Boolean
    package as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
Single formal parameter. R allows defaults and variadic `...` so both have to be tracked: has_default is set when the parser saw `name=value`, is_variadic is set when the lexeme was `...`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five fields: name, inferred RType, has_default flag, raw default_value string (re-evaluated lazily per R semantics), and is_variadic for the dots parameter.
@End Implementation

Type called "RParameter":
    name as String
    type as RType
    has_default as Boolean
    default_value as String
    is_variadic as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
R's type system is shape-aware: a numeric vector of length 5, a 3x4 matrix, and a data frame all share the same scalar base_type but differ in dimensions, attributes, and class. RType encodes all of that uniformly so the inferrer can reason about both element-level and shape-level operations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Seven fields: base_type (logical/integer/numeric/character/complex/raw/function/list/dataframe), dimensions list (empty for scalars/vectors, [rows,cols] for matrices), recursive element_type for nested structures, attribute dictionary for R's attr() system, factor handling (is_factor + factor_levels), and class_name for S3/S4 class tags.
@End Implementation

Type called "RType":
    base_type as String
    dimensions as List[Integer]
    element_type as RType
    attributes as Dictionary[String, String]
    is_factor as Boolean
    factor_levels as List[String]
    class_name as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
S3 is R's informal object system: a class is just a character vector of class names attached to an object, dispatched by method.classname conventions. RS3ClassInfo records the inheritance chain (parent_classes) and the methods registered against the class name so analyze_r_function_call can resolve dispatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four fields: class name, parent_classes list (the inheritance chain in NextMethod order), methods dictionary keyed by generic name, and an optional constructor function.
@End Implementation

Type called "RS3ClassInfo":
    class_name as String
    parent_classes as List[String]
    methods as Dictionary[String, RFunction]
    constructor as RFunction
End Type

@Reasoning:
S4 is R's formal object system: typed slots, formal method declarations via setMethod, and optional validity functions. Distinct from S3 because slots are checked at construction time. RS4ClassInfo records the slot schema, method table, and validator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five fields: class name, slot type dictionary (slot name -> RType), parent class chain, methods dictionary keyed by generic, and optional validity_function called by validObject().
@End Implementation

Type called "RS4ClassInfo":
    class_name as String
    slots as Dictionary[String, RType]
    parent_classes as List[String]
    methods as Dictionary[String, RFunction]
    validity_function as RFunction
End Type

@Reasoning:
Structured diagnostic record for semantic-phase errors and warnings. Distinct from parser errors because semantic errors require resolved symbols and inferred types; carrying the error_code lets the diagnostics layer group related findings and offer fixes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five fields: human-readable message, source line and column, severity ("error"/"warning"/"info"), and stable error_code (e.g. "R-SEM-001") for documentation cross-reference.
@End Implementation

Type called "RSemanticError":
    message as String
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    severity as String
    error_code as String
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN SEMANTIC ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver: creates a fresh global context, loads the base R package environments (base, stats, utils, graphics) plus the standard type registry, walks the AST via analyze_r_node, then runs final cross-cutting validations. The context returned is what r_to_hir consumes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_global_r_context, load_base_packages, load_standard_types, then dispatches analyze_r_node on the root, finally calls validate_r_semantics. Returns the fully-populated context.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_semantics" that takes ast as RASTNode returns RSemanticContext:
    Note: Main entry point for R semantic analysis

    @Reasoning:
    R has unique semantic requirements including dynamic typing, multiple
    object systems (S3/S4), environments for scoping, and statistical
    data types like data frames and factors.
    @End Reasoning

    Let context be create_global_r_context

    Note: Load standard R packages that are always available
    Call load_base_packages with context

    Note: Analyze the AST
    Call analyze_r_node with ast and context

    Note: Perform final validation
    Call validate_r_semantics with context

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory that constructs the analyzer's root context with a freshly-allocated global REnvironment, empty diagnostic lists, and empty S3/S4 registries. All subsequent analyze_* calls thread this context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds REnvironment (is_global=true), wraps it in an RSemanticContext with empty packages list, empty errors/warnings, empty type_cache, and empty s3_classes/s4_classes dictionaries.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_global_r_context" that takes nothing returns RSemanticContext:
    Note: Create the global semantic context with base R environment

    Let global_env be a value of type REnvironment with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_env as null,
        name as ".GlobalEnv",
        is_global as true

    Let context be a value of type RSemanticContext with
        current_environment as global_env,
        parent_context as null,
        global_packages as a list containing "base", "utils", "stats", "graphics", "grDevices", "methods", "datasets",
        current_function as null,
        error_list as a list containing nothing,
        warning_list as a list containing nothing,
        type_cache as a dictionary containing nothing,
        s3_classes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        s4_classes as a dictionary containing nothing

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bootstraps the always-loaded R packages: base, stats, utils, graphics, and the standard type table. Without these the analyzer would flag every call to c(), mean(), library(), or paste() as undefined.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequentially invokes load_base_functions, load_stats_functions, load_utils_functions, load_graphics_functions, then load_standard_types - each populates ctx.current_environment.functions and ctx.type_cache.
@End Implementation

Process called "load_base_packages" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load standard R packages and their functions

    @Reasoning:
    R comes with several standard packages that define built-in functions
    and data types. These need to be available in the global environment.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Load base package functions
    Call load_base_functions with ctx
    Call load_stats_functions with ctx
    Call load_utils_functions with ctx
    Call load_graphics_functions with ctx

    Note: Load standard data types
    Call load_standard_types with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the always-available functions defined in R's base package: c(), length(), names(), class(), print(), paste(), the is.* family, and the as.* coercion family. Without these, every R program would fail semantic checks because these calls have no declared origin.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a list of (name, RFunction) pairs using the create_*_function helpers, then installs each into ctx.current_environment.functions keyed by name. All entries are flagged with package="base" via their constructors.
@End Implementation

Process called "load_base_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load core R base functions

    Let base_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "c" and create_variadic_numeric_function,
        create_r_function with "length" and create_single_param_int_function,
        create_r_function with "names" and create_single_param_string_vector_function,
        create_r_function with "class" and create_single_param_string_vector_function,
        create_r_function with "str" and create_single_param_void_function,
        create_r_function with "summary" and create_single_param_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "head" and create_head_tail_function,
        create_r_function with "tail" and create_head_tail_function,
        create_r_function with "paste" and create_paste_function,
        create_r_function with "paste0" and create_paste0_function,
        create_r_function with "cat" and create_cat_function,
        create_r_function with "print" and create_print_function,
        create_r_function with "is.null" and create_is_null_function,
        create_r_function with "is.na" and create_is_na_function,
        create_r_function with "is.finite" and create_is_finite_function,
        create_r_function with "as.character" and create_as_character_function,
        create_r_function with "as.numeric" and create_as_numeric_function,
        create_r_function with "as.logical" and create_as_logical_function,
        create_r_function with "as.integer" and create_as_integer_function

    For Each func in base_functions:
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the canonical statistical procedures from R's stats package: descriptive (mean/median/sd/var/cor), regression (lm/glm/anova), hypothesis tests (t.test/chisq.test), and the random-number generators (rnorm/runif/etc.). These are the highest-frequency R calls in analytical code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a list of (name, RFunction) pairs using shape-appropriate helpers (stats_summary, regression, hypothesis test, random generation), then installs each into ctx.current_environment.functions keyed by name.
@End Implementation

Process called "load_stats_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load statistical functions from stats package

    Let stats_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "mean" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "median" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "sd" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "var" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "cor" and create_cor_function,
        create_r_function with "lm" and create_lm_function,
        create_r_function with "glm" and create_glm_function,
        create_r_function with "anova" and create_anova_function,
        create_r_function with "t.test" and create_t_test_function,
        create_r_function with "chisq.test" and create_chisq_test_function,
        create_r_function with "rnorm" and create_rnorm_function,
        create_r_function with "runif" and create_runif_function,
        create_r_function with "rbinom" and create_rbinom_function

    For Each func in stats_functions:
        Set func.package to "stats"
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers utility helpers from R's utils package: read.csv / read.table / write.csv for file I/O, help / installed.packages for environment introspection, and conversion / printing utilities.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a list of (name, RFunction) pairs for the utility helpers and installs each into ctx.current_environment.functions keyed by name.
@End Implementation

Process called "load_utils_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load utility functions from utils package

    Let utils_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "read.csv" and create_read_csv_function,
        create_r_function with "write.csv" and create_write_csv_function,
        create_r_function with "read.table" and create_read_table_function,
        create_r_function with "write.table" and create_write_table_function,
        create_r_function with "install.packages" and create_install_packages_function,
        create_r_function with "remove.packages" and create_remove_packages_function,
        create_r_function with "help" and create_help_function,
        create_r_function with "str" and create_str_function

    For Each func in utils_functions:
        Set func.package to "utils"
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the base graphics primitives: plot/lines/points/hist/boxplot/par/legend. These are the highest-frequency calls in R visualisation code; without them the analyzer would flag every chart-producing script.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a list of (name, RFunction) pairs using the graphics-specific helpers and installs each into ctx.current_environment.functions keyed by name.
@End Implementation

Process called "load_graphics_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load graphics functions

    Let graphics_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "plot" and create_plot_function,
        create_r_function with "hist" and create_hist_function,
        create_r_function with "boxplot" and create_boxplot_function,
        create_r_function with "barplot" and create_barplot_function,
        create_r_function with "pie" and create_pie_function,
        create_r_function with "lines" and create_lines_function,
        create_r_function with "points" and create_points_function,
        create_r_function with "legend" and create_legend_function

    For Each func in graphics_functions:
        Set func.package to "graphics"
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pre-populates the type cache with the canonical R atomic types - logical, integer, numeric (double), character, complex, raw - plus the compound types vector, list, matrix, array, data.frame, and factor. infer_*_type routines query these names rather than rebuilding them on each lookup.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds one RType per standard type via the create_*_type factories and stores each in ctx.type_cache keyed by base_type name.
@End Implementation

Process called "load_standard_types" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load standard R data types

    @Reasoning:
    R has unique data types like data.frame, factor, matrix, list, etc.
    These need to be registered in the type system for proper validation.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Register basic R types
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "logical" to create_logical_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "integer" to create_integer_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "numeric" to create_numeric_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "complex" to create_complex_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "character" to create_character_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "raw" to create_raw_type

    Note: Register complex R types
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "data.frame" to create_data_frame_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "list" to create_list_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "matrix" to create_matrix_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "array" to create_array_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "factor" to create_factor_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "function" to create_function_type

    Note: Register S3 classes
    Call register_s3_classes with ctx

    Note: Register S4 classes
    Call register_s4_classes with ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST NODE ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Polymorphic dispatcher: drives the entire semantic walk. Each AST node type routes to its dedicated analyze_r_* routine. Centralising the switch here keeps the recursion structure flat and lets new node types be added without touching every caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on node.node_type string: "program" -> analyze_r_program, "function_decl" -> analyze_r_function_declaration, "variable_decl" -> analyze_r_variable_declaration, "assignment" -> analyze_r_assignment, "call" -> analyze_r_function_call, "formula" -> analyze_r_formula, "library_call" -> analyze_r_library_call, "dataframe_access" -> analyze_r_dataframe_access. Unknown types are silently ignored (forward compatible).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_node" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze any R AST node based on its type

    Match node.node_type:
        When "Program":
            Call analyze_r_program with node and ctx
        When "FunctionDeclaration":
            Call analyze_r_function_declaration with node and ctx
        When "VariableDeclaration":
            Call analyze_r_variable_declaration with node and ctx
        When "Assignment":
            Call analyze_r_assignment with node and ctx
        When "FunctionCall":
            Call analyze_r_function_call with node and ctx
        When "FormulaExpression":
            Call analyze_r_formula with node and ctx
        When "LibraryCall":
            Call analyze_r_library_call with node and ctx
        When "DataFrameAccess":
            Call analyze_r_dataframe_access with node and ctx
        When "VectorOperation":
            Call analyze_r_vector_operation with node and ctx
        When "IfStatement":
            Call analyze_r_if_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForLoop":
            Call analyze_r_for_loop with node and ctx
        When "WhileLoop":
            Call analyze_r_while_loop with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Call analyze_generic_node with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks each top-level statement of a program node. Statements run in source order so later bindings can shadow earlier ones, matching R's interpretive semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates node.statements and calls analyze_r_node on each. No early exit on errors - the goal is to surface as many issues as possible per analysis pass.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_program" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R program (top-level statements)

    For Each statement in node.statements:
        Call analyze_r_node with statement and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a function definition into the current environment, creates a child environment with its formal parameters bound, recursively analyzes the body in that child environment, then unwinds back. This is where lexical scoping is realized in the analyzer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an RFunction from node.function_name, node.parameters, with inferred return_type. Inserts into ctx.current_environment.functions. Creates child env via create_function_environment, binds each parameter as an RVariable, swaps ctx.current_environment, analyzes node.body, then restores the parent environment.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_function_declaration" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R function declaration

    @Reasoning:
    R functions can be assigned to variables and have complex parameter
    handling including default values, variadic arguments (...), and
    lazy evaluation.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_name be node.name
    Let parameters be node.parameters
    Let body be node.body

    Note: Create function environment
    Let func_env be create_function_environment with ctx.current_environment and func_name

    Note: Analyze parameters
    Let r_params be a list containing nothing
    For Each param as RASTNode in parameters:
        Let r_param be analyze_r_parameter with param and ctx of type RParameter
        Add r_param to end of r_params

        Note: Add parameter to function environment
        Let param_var be a value of type RVariable with
            name as param.name,
            type as r_param.type,
            is_constant as false,
            scope as func_name,
            first_assignment_line as param.line,
            last_access_line as param.line

        Set func_env.variables at key param.name to param_var
    End For

    Note: Create function object
    Let r_function be a value of type RFunction with
        name as func_name,
        parameters as r_params,
        return_type as create_any_type,
        is_generic as false,
        is_s3_method as check_is_s3_method with func_name,
        is_s4_method as check_is_s4_method with func_name,
        package as null

    Note: Set function context and analyze body
    Let old_env be ctx.current_environment
    Let old_func be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_environment to func_env
    Set ctx.current_function to func_name

    Call analyze_r_node with body and ctx

    Note: Restore context
    Set ctx.current_environment to old_env
    Set ctx.current_function to old_func

    Note: Register function in environment
    Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func_name to r_function
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a new variable binding and infers its initial type from the initializer expression. R has no explicit declaration syntax - "declaration" here means the first assignment - so this also tracks first_assignment_line for the lifetime checks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Infers RType via infer_r_expression_type on node.initializer. Constructs an RVariable with name, inferred type, first_assignment_line=node.line, last_access_line=0, is_constant=false. Inserts into ctx.current_environment.variables.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_variable_declaration" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R variable declaration

    Let var_name be node.name
    Let var_type be node.node_type
    Let initializer be node.initializer

    Note: Check if variable already exists
    If ctx.current_environment.variables contains key var_name:
        Let warning be "Variable '" joined with var_name joined with "' already exists and will be overwritten"
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Infer type from initializer if present
    Let inferred_type be create_any_type
    If initializer is not equal to 0:
        Set inferred_type to infer_r_expression_type with initializer and ctx
        Call analyze_r_node with initializer and ctx
    End If

    Note: Create variable
    Let r_variable be a value of type RVariable with
        name as var_name,
        type as inferred_type,
        is_constant as false,
        scope as ctx.current_environment.name,
        first_assignment_line as node.line,
        last_access_line as node.line

    Set ctx.current_environment.variables at key var_name to r_variable
End Process

@Reasoning:
Handles R's five assignment operators (<-, <<-, =, ->, ->>). The "super-assign" operators <<-/->> climb the environment chain looking for an existing binding rather than creating a local one; this routine implements that lookup semantics so the analyzer's symbol tables stay accurate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspects node.operator. For <-/=/->, looks up target in current env: if missing, treats as variable_decl; if present, updates type and last_assignment_line. For <<-/->>, walks parent_env chain until binding found (or global if none), then updates that.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_assignment" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R assignment operations

    @Reasoning:
    R supports multiple assignment operators: <-, =, ->, <<-, and ->>
    Each has different semantics for scope and evaluation.
    @End Reasoning

    Let target be node.target
    Let value be node.value
    Let operator be node.operator

    Note: Analyze value expression first
    Call analyze_r_node with value and ctx
    Let value_type be infer_r_expression_type with value and ctx

    Note: Handle different assignment types
    Match operator:
        When "<-":
            Call analyze_left_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "=":
            Call analyze_equal_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "->":
            Call analyze_right_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "<<-":
            Call analyze_global_left_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "->>":
            Call analyze_global_right_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Let error be "Unknown assignment operator: " joined with operator
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves the callee, checks the call site against the function's known parameter list (arity, named arg names), recursively analyzes each argument expression, and updates last_access_line for any referenced functions/variables.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Looks up node.function_name via lookup_r_function. Iterates node.arguments calling analyze_r_node on each, then matches positional and named arguments against the function's parameters. Reports diagnostics for unknown names, missing required parameters, or arity mismatches.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_function_call" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R function call

    Let func_name be node.function_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments

    Note: Check if function exists
    Let r_function be lookup_r_function with func_name and ctx
    If r_function is equal to 0:
        Note: Check for S3 method dispatch
        Let s3_method be check_s3_method_dispatch with func_name and arguments and ctx of type RFunction
        If s3_method is not equal to 0:
            Set r_function to s3_method
        End If
    End If

    If r_function is equal to 0:
        Let error be "Function '" joined with func_name joined with "' not found"
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Analyze arguments
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Call analyze_r_node with arg and ctx
    End For

    Note: Check argument compatibility
    Call validate_r_function_arguments with r_function and arguments and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
R formulas (y ~ x1 + x2:x3) describe statistical model structure. They are first-class values - lm(y~x, data=df) passes the formula unevaluated. The analyzer must resolve response/predictors as variable references but defer their use semantics to the consuming function (lm, glm, etc.).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records the formula's response variable and predictor list against the current environment. Walks predictors and interactions (a:b terms) marking each name as an access. Builds an RType with base_type="formula".
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_formula" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R formula expressions (y ~ x)

    @Reasoning:
    R formulas are special expressions used in statistical modeling.
    They have specific syntax and semantic rules for variable references.
    @End Reasoning

    Let response be node.response
    Let predictors be node.predictors
    Let interactions be node.interactions

    Note: Analyze response variable
    If response is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with response and ctx
        Call validate_formula_variable with response and ctx
    End If

    Note: Analyze predictor variables
    For Each predictor in predictors:
        Call analyze_r_node with predictor and ctx
        Call validate_formula_variable with predictor and ctx
    End For

    Note: Analyze interactions
    For Each interaction in interactions:
        Call analyze_r_interaction with interaction and ctx
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
library()/require() loads a package's exports into the search path. Both are recorded here so subsequent function lookups can resolve names exported by the package. require() returns FALSE on missing package while library() errors; the is_require flag distinguishes the call shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node.package_name and node.is_require. Appends to ctx.global_packages if not already present. validate_package_dependencies later confirms each name corresponds to a known package descriptor.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_library_call" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze library/require calls

    Let package_name be node.package_name
    Let is_require be node.is_require

    Note: Check if package is already loaded
    If ctx.global_packages contains package_name:
        If not is_require:
            Let warning be "Package '" joined with package_name joined with "' already loaded"
            Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
        Return
    End If

    Note: Load package functions and types
    Call load_package_definitions with package_name and ctx

    Note: Add to loaded packages
    Add package_name to end of ctx.global_packages
End Process

@Reasoning:
Data frame access has shape-dependent semantics: df$col returns a vector (the column), df[i,j] preserves data.frame class, df[[i]] returns the raw column. The analyzer needs to infer which is happening so consumers see the correct downstream type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspects node.access_type ("$" / "[" / "[[") to select the proper return-type construction: column access yields the column's element type, [i,j] yields a data.frame subset, [[i]] yields the column type. Records that node.dataframe is being accessed for use-tracking.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_dataframe_access" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze data frame access operations (df$col, df[row, col])

    Let dataframe be node.dataframe
    Let accessor be node.accessor
    Let access_type be node.access_type

    Note: Analyze dataframe expression
    Call analyze_r_node with dataframe and ctx
    Let df_type be infer_r_expression_type with dataframe and ctx

    Note: Validate it's actually a data frame
    If df_type.base_type is not equal to "data.frame":
        Let error be "Attempting data frame access on non-data.frame object"
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Analyze accessor based on type
    Match access_type:
        When "column":
            Call analyze_column_access with accessor and df_type and ctx
        When "row":
            Call analyze_row_access with accessor and df_type and ctx
        When "subset":
            Call analyze_subset_access with accessor and df_type and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Set error to "Unknown data frame access type: " joined with access_type
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE INFERENCE AND VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level type inferrer. Returns the RType of any expression, dispatching on node shape. The result is used both for assignment target-type recording and for argument shape-checking in function calls.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on expr.node_type: literal -> infer_literal_type, identifier -> infer_identifier_type, function_call -> infer_function_call_type, formula -> create_formula_type, dataframe_access -> shape-aware inference. Falls back to create_any_type for unknown shapes (rather than failing, which would be over-eager).
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_r_expression_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Note: Infer the type of an R expression

    @Reasoning:
    R is dynamically typed but we can infer types for better error checking
    and optimization. This handles R's unique type system including vectors,
    factors, and data frames.
    @End Reasoning

    Match expr.type:
        When "Literal":
            Return infer_literal_type with expr
        When "Identifier":
            Return infer_identifier_type with expr and ctx
        When "FunctionCall":
            Return infer_function_call_type with expr and ctx
        When "VectorConstruction":
            Return infer_vector_type with expr and ctx
        When "DataFrameConstruction":
            Return infer_data_frame_type with expr and ctx
        When "BinaryOperation":
            Return infer_binary_operation_type with expr and ctx
        When "UnaryOperation":
            Return infer_unary_operation_type with expr and ctx
        When "FormulaExpression":
            Return create_formula_type
        Otherwise:
            Return create_any_type
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps the lexer-attached literal_type back to a canonical RType. R has rich literal taxonomy: 1L is integer, 1 is numeric (double), 1i is complex, "x" is character, TRUE/FALSE/NA are logical, NULL is null.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on expr.literal_type integer code: TOKEN_NUMBER -> create_numeric_type, TOKEN_INTEGER -> create_integer_type, TOKEN_STRING -> create_character_type, TOKEN_TRUE/FALSE -> create_logical_type, TOKEN_COMPLEX -> create_complex_type, TOKEN_NULL -> NULL RType.
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_literal_type" that takes expr as RASTNode returns RType:
    Note: Infer type from literal values

    Let value be expr.value
    Let literal_type be expr.literal_type

    Match literal_type:
        When "integer":
            Return create_integer_type
        When "numeric":
            Return create_numeric_type
        When "character":
            Return create_character_type
        When "logical":
            Return create_logical_type
        When "complex":
            Return create_complex_type
        When "raw":
            Return create_raw_type
        Otherwise:
            Return create_any_type
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves a bare identifier to its declared variable's type. Falls back to create_any_type if the binding cannot be found (R is dynamic, so undefined-at-analysis is a warning, not an error).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls lookup_r_variable with expr.name. If found, returns the bound variable's RType and bumps last_access_line. If not found, emits a warning into ctx and returns create_any_type.
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_identifier_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Note: Infer type from variable reference

    Let var_name be expr.name

    Note: Look up variable in current environment
    Let variable be lookup_r_variable with var_name and ctx
    If variable is not equal to 0:
        Set variable.last_access_line to expr.line
        Return variable.type
    End If

    Note: Check if it's a function
    Let function be lookup_r_function with var_name and ctx
    If function is not equal to 0:
        Return create_function_type
    End If

    Note: Unknown identifier - could be created dynamically
    Let warning be "Unknown identifier: " joined with var_name
    Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    Return create_any_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the inferred result type of a function call by looking up the callee and reading its declared return_type. R can return Any (the "anything" type) for highly polymorphic functions like c() or paste(), in which case downstream logic must handle the Any case explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls lookup_r_function with expr.function_name. On hit, returns the function's return_type RType. On miss, emits a warning and returns create_any_type.
@End Implementation

Process called "infer_function_call_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Note: Infer return type from function call

    Let func_name be expr.function_name
    Let r_function be lookup_r_function with func_name and ctx

    If r_function is not equal to 0:
        Return r_function.return_type
    End If

    Note: Try S3 method dispatch
    Let s3_method be check_s3_method_dispatch with func_name and expr.arguments and ctx of type RFunction
    If s3_method is not equal to 0:
        Return s3_method.return_type
    End If

    Note: Unknown function
    Return create_any_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Walks the environment chain from current_environment up through parent_env links until either the binding is found or the global environment is exhausted. This is the runtime-faithful lookup R uses for symbol resolution under lexical scoping.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates env = ctx.current_environment; while env != null: if env.variables contains name, return that RVariable; else env = env.parent_env. Returns null on chain exhaustion.
@End Implementation

Process called "lookup_r_variable" that takes name as String, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RVariable:
    Note: Look up variable in environment chain

    Let current_env be ctx.current_environment
    While current_env is not equal to 0:
        If current_env.variables contains key name:
            Return current_env.variables at key name
        End If
        Set current_env to current_env.parent_env
    End While

    Return null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of lookup_r_variable for the functions dictionary. R's evaluation model separates value bindings from function bindings only when resolving the head of a call expression, but the storage in REnvironment is also split so this walks the same chain.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates env = ctx.current_environment; while env != null: if env.functions contains name, return that RFunction; else env = env.parent_env. Returns null on chain exhaustion.
@End Implementation

Process called "lookup_r_function" that takes name as String, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RFunction:
    Note: Look up function in environment chain

    Let current_env be ctx.current_environment
    While current_env is not equal to 0:
        If current_env.functions contains key name:
            Return current_env.functions at key name
        End If
        Set current_env to current_env.parent_env
    End While

    Return null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs a child REnvironment for entering a function body. The parent_env link captures R's lexical scoping (functions see the environment where they were defined, not where they're called from).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an REnvironment with empty variables/functions dictionaries, parent_env=parent, name=func_name, is_global=false.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_function_environment" that takes parent as REnvironment, func_name as String returns REnvironment:
    Note: Create new environment for function scope

    Return a value of type REnvironment with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_env as parent,
        name as func_name,
        is_global as false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cross-cutting validation pass run after the full AST walk. Catches issues that can only be diagnosed once everything has been registered: unused variables, never-called functions, missing package loads, malformed S3/S4 method tables.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequentially invokes validate_variable_usage, validate_function_usage, validate_package_dependencies, validate_s3_methods, validate_s4_methods. Each appends diagnostics to ctx.error_list or ctx.warning_list.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_r_semantics" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform final semantic validation

    @Reasoning:
    Final validation checks for issues that can only be detected after
    the full AST has been analyzed, such as undefined variables used
    in formulas or missing required packages.
    @End Reasoning

    Call validate_variable_usage with ctx
    Call validate_function_usage with ctx
    Call validate_package_dependencies with ctx
    Call validate_s3_methods with ctx
    Call validate_s4_methods with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports variables that were assigned but never accessed (first_assignment_line set, last_access_line still 0). Reported as warnings rather than errors because R legitimately has many side-effect-only assignments (e.g. saving a result to .Rdata).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates ctx.current_environment.variables. For each RVariable where last_access_line is 0, appends a "warning: unused variable" entry to ctx.warning_list with the first_assignment_line as source location.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_variable_usage" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate all variables were properly used

    Note: This  check for unused variables, uninitialized usage, etc.
    Note: Implementation depends on tracking variable access patterns
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cross-checks function-call invariants captured during analyze_r_function_call: ensures every callee was resolvable, that no required parameter was left without a positional or named arg, and that all named arguments correspond to declared formals.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks ctx.error_list / ctx.warning_list for already-flagged call-site issues and elevates patterns that indicate hard errors (e.g. arity mismatch) versus warnings (e.g. dynamic dispatch fallback).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_function_usage" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate function calls are correct

    Note: This  check argument counts, types, etc.
    Note: Implementation depends on detailed function signature tracking
End Process

@Reasoning:
Confirms every package mentioned in a library()/require() call is one the analyzer knows how to model. Unknown packages become warnings (analysis falls back to Any types) rather than errors so working-but-novel R code still translates.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates ctx.global_packages. For each name that does not appear in the analyzer's package registry, appends a "warning: unknown package" entry to ctx.warning_list.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_package_dependencies" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate required packages are loaded

    Note: Check if functions from unloaded packages are being used
End Process

@Reasoning:
Checks that every registered S3 method follows the `generic.class` naming convention and that each generic has at least one method defined. Misnamed methods are silent traps in real R code; warning here surfaces them at translation time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates ctx.s3_classes. For each RS3ClassInfo, scans the methods dictionary verifying naming pattern. Appends warnings for any method whose name does not split correctly into generic + class.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_s3_methods" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate S3 method definitions and usage

    Note: Check S3 generic/method consistency
End Process

@Reasoning:
Checks that every S4 class has slots with declared types, that methods reference declared classes, and that any validity_function attached takes the class as its sole argument. S4 is stricter than S3 so these checks are hard errors.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates ctx.s4_classes. For each RS4ClassInfo, verifies slot RTypes are present, methods reference an existing parent class, and validity_function has exactly one parameter. Appends errors for any mismatch.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_s4_methods" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate S4 method definitions and usage

    Note: Check S4 class definitions and method signatures
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE CREATION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Factory for the logical scalar RType. R's logical type is tri-valued (TRUE, FALSE, NA) - the NA case is handled at runtime by the bit pattern of the value, not by the type. Type creation is parameterless because logical scalars have no extra shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "logical", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_logical_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "logical",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the integer scalar RType. In R, integer is the 32-bit type distinguished from numeric (double) by the L suffix on literals (42L). Inference distinguishes the two so codegen can pick the right storage width.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "integer", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_integer_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "integer",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the numeric (double-precision) scalar RType. R's default arithmetic type - bare literals like 3.14 or 42 (without L suffix) are numeric. IEEE 754 double precision.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "numeric", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_numeric_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "numeric",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the character (string) scalar RType. R calls strings "character" - distinct from C's "string" because R character vectors carry one string per element rather than one character per element.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "character", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_character_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "character",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the complex (a+bi) scalar RType. Produced by the i-suffix lexer rule (3i, 2.5i). Backed by a pair of IEEE 754 doubles for real and imaginary parts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "complex", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_complex_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "complex",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the raw (single-byte) scalar RType. R's raw vectors are arbitrary byte arrays - used for binary I/O and serialization. Distinct from integer because no arithmetic is defined.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "raw", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_raw_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "raw",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the data.frame compound RType. Data frames are R's tabular data primitive - a list of equal-length vectors with column names. The class_name field is also set to "data.frame" so S3 dispatch on print/[.data.frame/etc. works.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "data.frame" and class_name "data.frame"; other fields nulled or empty (column schema is recorded in attributes by callers that have specific columns).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_data_frame_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "data.frame",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as "data.frame"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the function-as-value RType. R functions are first-class - they can be assigned to variables, passed as arguments, returned from other functions. This type is used when infer_identifier_type sees a name bound to a function rather than a value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "function", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_function_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "function",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the dynamic "Any" RType used as the fallback when inference cannot pin down a more specific type. Lets the analyzer continue rather than fail on R's pervasive dynamism (e.g. mixed-type lists, runtime-dispatched function returns).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "any", all other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_any_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "any",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the formula RType (y ~ x1 + x2). Formulas are first-class R values consumed unevaluated by modelling functions (lm, glm, aggregate). class_name is also "formula" so S3 method dispatch resolves.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an RType with base_type "formula" and class_name "formula"; other fields nulled or empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_formula_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "formula",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as "formula"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Base Function Creation Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Factory for the c() function signature - the canonical variadic constructor in R that combines values into a vector. Variadic via the `...` parameter; returns a numeric (the type coerces upward if heterogeneous arguments are seen at runtime).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an RParameter named "..." with is_variadic=true and Any element type, then returns an RFunction named "c" with that single parameter, return_type=numeric, package="base".
@End Implementation

Process called "create_variadic_numeric_function" that takes nothing returns RFunction:
    Note: Create c() function signature

    Let param be a value of type RParameter with
        name as "...",
        type as create_any_type,
        has_default as false,
        default_value as null,
        is_variadic as true

    Return a value of type RFunction with
        name as "c",
        parameters as a list containing param,
        return_type as create_numeric_type,
        is_generic as false,
        is_s3_method as false,
        is_s4_method as false,
        package as "base"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for length() and similar single-parameter integer-returning functions. length() takes one argument of any type and returns its element count as an integer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an RParameter named "x" with Any type, returns an RFunction named "length" with that single parameter, return_type=integer, package="base".
@End Implementation

Process called "create_single_param_int_function" that takes nothing returns RFunction:
    Note: Create length() function signature

    Let param be a value of type RParameter with
        name as "x",
        type as create_any_type,
        has_default as false,
        default_value as null,
        is_variadic as false

    Return a value of type RFunction with
        name as "length",
        parameters as a list containing param,
        return_type as create_integer_type,
        is_generic as false,
        is_s3_method as false,
        is_s4_method as false,
        package as "base"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for names()/class() and similar single-parameter character-vector-returning functions. These take one argument of any type and return a character vector describing it (the column names for a data frame, the class chain for any object).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an RParameter named "x" with Any type, returns an RFunction named "names" with that single parameter, return_type=character, package="base".
@End Implementation

Process called "create_single_param_string_vector_function" that takes nothing returns RFunction:
    Note: Create names()/class() function signatures

    Let param be a value of type RParameter with
        name as "x",
        type as create_any_type,
        has_default as false,
        default_value as null,
        is_variadic as false

    Return a value of type RFunction with
        name as "names",
        parameters as a list containing param,
        return_type as create_character_type,
        is_generic as false,
        is_s3_method as false,
        is_s4_method as false,
        package as "base"
End Process

Note: Entry point for R semantic analysis
@Reasoning:
Thin facade over analyze_r_semantics provided for naming-consistency with the other frontends (which all expose analyze_X_semantic_tree as their public entry point). Identical semantics to analyze_r_semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates directly to analyze_r_semantics(ast) and returns its result.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_r_semantic_tree" that takes ast as RASTNode returns RSemanticContext:
    Return analyze_r_semantics with ast
End Process